# Java Logging

## Facade
- Use SLF4J as the logging facade: `private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MyClass.class)`
- Backend: Logback (Spring Boot default) or Log4j2
- Never use `System.out.println` or `System.err.println` for logging

## Log Levels
| Level | Usage |
|-------|-------|
| ERROR | System failures, unrecoverable errors, SLA-impacting events |
| WARN | Recoverable issues, degraded behavior, approaching limits |
| INFO | Business events, request lifecycle, configuration changes |
| DEBUG | Developer diagnostics, method entry/exit, variable state |
| TRACE | Fine-grained debugging, loop iterations (avoid in production) |

## Message Formatting
- Parameterized messages: `log.info("Order {} processed in {}ms", orderId, elapsed)`
- Never concatenate strings: avoid `log.debug("User " + name + " logged in")`
- Include relevant context: entity IDs, operation type, timing

## Structured Logging
- Use structured JSON logging in production (Logstash encoder or structured-arguments)
- Include correlation/request IDs via MDC (Mapped Diagnostic Context) or ScopedValue
- Add key-value pairs: `log.info("Payment processed", kv("orderId", id), kv("amount", total))`

## What to Log
- Request/response at API boundaries (INFO, exclude sensitive data)
- State transitions and business decisions (INFO)
- External service calls with timing (INFO/DEBUG)
- Configuration at startup (INFO)
- Exceptions with stack traces at ERROR level only for unexpected failures

## What NOT to Log
- Passwords, tokens, API keys, PII, credit card numbers
- Entire request/response bodies in production (use DEBUG for development)
- Redundant messages (log-and-throw duplicates)
- High-frequency events at INFO level (use DEBUG or sampling)

## Performance
- Guard expensive log construction: `if (log.isDebugEnabled()) { log.debug(...) }`
- Use lazy evaluation with suppliers for expensive arguments
- Async appenders for high-throughput services

